ity, and legitimacy of local scenes—cafes, churches, restaurants, parks, galleries, bowling alleys, and more. Scenescapes not only reimagines cities in cultural terms, it details how scenes shape economic development, residential patterns, and political attitudes and actions. In vivid detail and with wide-angle analyses—encompassing an analysis of 40,000 ZIP codes—Silver and Clark give readers tools for thinking about place; tools that can teach us where to live, work, or relax, and how to organize our communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPlace (Philosophy)xSocial aspects. 0aSituation (Philosophy)xSocial aspects. 0aSocial ecology. 0aSociology, Urban. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aamenities.  acities.  aculture.  ascenes.  aurban development.  aurban studies.1 aClark, Terry Nichols, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUrban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019z97831106385160 cprintz978022635685340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226357041423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226357041/original  a978-3-11-063851-6  Urban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019c2016d2019  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles